# Meeting #2 — IDSA Task Force on Data Spaces and AI

**Date:** 8 May 2026 · **Time:** 11:00 – 12:00 CET · **Format:** Microsoft Teams (recorded)

---

## Meeting highlights

**Task Force name.** The group discussed the voting results on the Task Force name. Olaf proposed reversing the order to "Data Spaces and AI" — arguing that IDSA is a data spaces association and AI is a tool, so data spaces should come first. Roland, Reinhold, and Achim agreed. Roland added that "without data, your AI might become very stupid" and recommended avoiding words like "architecture" or "integration" in the name as they narrow the audience. Reinhold supported keeping the name simple and general. No objections were raised. The Task Force is now officially named **Data Spaces and AI**.

**Backlog prioritization results.** Anil presented the grouped backlog items and the voting results. While the number of votes was limited, there was a clear tendency toward producing a position/scoping paper as the primary deliverable by end of June.

**Audience and communication.** Olaf stressed that the paper must be readable by non-technical audiences — mayors, journalists, and decision-makers — not just insiders. He warned that writing in acronyms limits impact and proposed supplementing the paper with an online presence: a website with practical examples, a radar-style overview of implementations, and visuals. Achim countered that the priority should be doing the groundbreaking technical work first, and that communication and outreach can be handled afterwards by communication professionals or even AI tools. Reinhold proposed a middle ground: a paper written for a broad audience, technically correct but easy to read, with links to technical detail papers for readers who want to go deeper.

**AI agents in data spaces — Reinhold's framing.** Reinhold shared three slides with the group. His core message: data spaces already solve several challenges AI faces today — data quality (known providers), data availability (trusted environment encourages sharing), access definitions (clear policies and usage conditions), compensation, observability through logging, governance and automation, and agent discovery. The Dataspace Protocol enables easy integration of AI agents: they simply need a connector. No additional IDSA definitions are needed. In the data plane, AI applications can use their own protocols after agreeing on terms in the control plane.

**AI agents as "super automated humans".** Peter argued that an AI agent can do anything in a data space that a human actor could do through whatever interface the human has. The paper should be short and focused: the data space idea does not change just because it is an agent using EDC instead of a human. He shared that his GitHub Copilot figured out how EDC works and built a skill for itself in less than an afternoon. Peter also raised a forward-looking question: how will data space organizations change when agents do not need annual board meetings or associations — just verifiable credentials?

**Pushback on implementation details.** Mohammad pushed back on the idea that nothing changes. While the general data space concept holds, implementation requirements shift when agents operate: connectors must handle much higher request frequencies, and negotiation phases may involve far more messages than human-to-human exchanges. Peter acknowledged this but classified it as an implementation detail for Eclipse projects and providers, not a fundamental IDSA requirement. Both agreed that the organizational change question is worth exploring.

**Future testbed.** Akira expressed interest in expanding IDSA's activity toward a testbed or conformance testing for interoperability, and suggested mentioning this as a future direction in the paper.

**Paper structure.** Anil opened the Miro board for a collaborative exercise on structuring the position/scoping paper. Participants added chapters (violet stickies) and subchapters (yellow stickies). Achim contributed a detailed structure and offered to contribute to the chapters he marked. The board remains open for further contributions.

**Paper timeline.** Anil presented a timeline for the paper. The group will compile entries and draft the outline and table of contents by 13 May, review and finalize the ToC with section assignments by 16 May, deliver first drafts by 15 June, conduct an internal review during the Task Force meeting on 19 June, and complete editorial rework by 30 June for publication.

**New members.** Petteri Kivimäki (NIIS, CTO and co-chair of WG Architecture) joined for the first time, giving the Task Force representation from both core IDSA working groups. Viivi Lähteenoja (1001 Lakes) joined bringing a data strategy and policy perspective. Arian Firouzbakhsh (NTT Data, former IDSA RA group chair and IDSA ambassador) rejoined the IDSA community through this Task Force.

---

## Decisions

- Task Force officially renamed to **Data Spaces and AI**
- Position/scoping paper confirmed as the primary deliverable for 30 June
- Paper should target a broad, non-technical audience — technically correct but easy to read, with links to technical details
- No additional IDSA definitions needed to integrate AI agents — apply existing assets (DSP, RAM, Rulebook)
- Paper timeline agreed: outline by 13 May, first draft by 15 June, publication 30 June
- Miro board remains open for structure contributions

